the issue is autofill is not working in the react-phone-number-input



I've analyzed the GitHub issue and your code. The problem is that the PhoneInput component doesn't work properly with browser autofill despite showing the dropdown suggestions.

Here's how to fix the issue:

```tsx
<FormControl
  isRequired
  isInvalid={!!errors?.phone?.message}
  mt="16px"
>
  <FormLabel htmlFor="phone-input">{t("Appointment.form.fieldMobile.label")}</FormLabel>
  <Controller
    name="phone"
    control={control}
    rules={{ validate: validatePhone }}
    render={({ field }) => (
      <div style={{ position: "relative", width: "100%", backgroundColor: "transparent" }}>
        {/* Hidden input for autofill capture */}
        <input
          type="tel"
          id="phone-autofill"
          name="phone"
          autoComplete="tel mobile"
          style={{ display: 'none' }}
          onChange={(e) => {
            if (e.target.value) {
              // When browser autofill triggers, update the phone input
              setValue('phone', e.target.value);
              trigger('phone');
            }
          }}
        />
        <PhoneInput
          {...field}
          id="phone-input"
          international
          defaultCountry="IT"
          placeholder={t("Appointment.form.fieldMobile.placeholder")}
          onChange={async (value: string | undefined) => {
            await handleFieldChange("phone", value ?? "");
          }}
        />
      </div>
    )}
  />
  <FormErrorMessage>{errors?.phone?.message}</FormErrorMessage>
</FormControl>
```

The trick is to add a hidden native input field that captures the browser's autofill data, and then programmatically update the PhoneInput component's value when autofill happens.

The hidden input uses `autoComplete="tel mobile"` to tell browsers it's for phone numbers, and it has the `name="phone"` attribute which helps browser autofill identify it. When the hidden input receives autofill data, we update the form state with that value.
